SIMPLE: singularity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Singularity
<hw>Sin`gu*lar"i*ty</hw>
<pr>(s⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧`g⟦usl⟧*l⟦acr⟧r"⟦icr⟧*t⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Singularities</plw>
<pr>(s⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧`g⟦usl⟧*l⟦acr⟧r"⟦icr⟧*t⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>singularitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>singularit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being singular; some character
or quality of a thing by which it is distinguished from all, or from
most, others; peculiarity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pliny addeth this <qex>singularity</qex> to that soil, that the
second year the very falling down of the seeds yieldeth corn.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir. W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I took notice of this little figure for the <qex>singularity</qex>
of the instrument.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything singular, rare, or curious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your gallery⟦br⟧
Have we passed through, not without much content⟦br⟧
In many <qex>singularities</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Possession of a particular or exclusive privilege,
prerogative, or distinction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No bishop of Rome ever took upon him this name of
<qex>singularity</qex> [universal bishop].</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Catholicism . . . must be understood in opposition to the legal
<qex>singularity</qex> of the Jewish nation.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Pearson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Celibacy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Jer.
Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Singularize</ent>⟦br⟧
